default3. Is disqualifying prisoners from voting a suitable part of their punishment?default&#xa0;
defaultNo.
default 
defaultDisqualifying prisoners from voting should not be part of their punishment, unless the 
defaultprisoner has committed electoral offences which violate the democratic process e.g. postal voting fraud or misfeasance in a public office. Here the punishment is linked to the crime and could have a rational basis
default for 
defaulta temporary ban
default. T
defaulthe Strasbourg Court has accepted
default this
default as a legitimate g
defaultround for a temporary ban in 
defaultMDU v Italy
default App. No. 58400/00 (23 January 2003).
default&#xa0;
defaultBut 
defaultotherwise i
defaultt is 
defaultdifficult to justify an additional punishment as the prison sentence is 
defaultthe
default punishment. 
defaultDisenfranchisement
default bears no relati
defaulton to the ty
defaultpe of crime or gravity of the crime.
default It is 
defaultdisproportionate and it can be seen a
defaults a
default degrading punishment reducing
default the 
defaultoffender to a state of civil death. 
defaultIt is
default also an
default arbitrary punishment as it depends on the timing of the elections.
default It 
defaultis
default 
defaultunlikely to deter offenders or the general public from committing crimes.
default 
defaultIt does not contribute to the rehabilitation of
default p
defaultrisoners. On the contrary
default,
default it reinforces their social exclusion. Conversely
default,
default allowing prisoners t
defaulto
default vote might encourage prisoners to reflect on their civic obligations and ultimately have positive implications in reducing re
default-
defaultoffending
default and 
defaultr
defaulteinforcing 
defaulttheir sense of having a stake in their 
defaultcommunity on release.
default Research by Uggen and Manza in the United States found differences between voters and non-voters in their rates of subsequent arrest, incarc
defaulter
defaultation and self reported criminal behaviour.
default 
defaultIt is also not 
defaultnecessary for public protection. There is no risk to the public in granting the vote
default 
defaultto 
defaultprisoners
default regardless of sentence length
